You are a senior Rust library reviewer. A pure-Rust wgpu 2D graphics/game engine (plutonium_engine v0.8.0) was audited for crates.io / open-source readiness. Below are the finding TITLES grouped by dimension. Answer TWO questions concisely (bullet points, cite a concrete area):
Q1. What SIGNIFICANT production/open-source-readiness issues are MISSING from this list that a Rust graphics-library reviewer would expect? (e.g. things about Send/Sync, panics in Drop, surface-loss recovery, color-space/sRGB correctness, HiDPI edge cases, no-std, docs.rs metadata, semver/CI, licensing of bundled font assets, etc.) Only list ones likely to actually apply.
Q2. Which listed findings are TRIVIAL or speculative and should be DROPPED before promotion to a fix queue?

FINDINGS:
[CORRECTNESS] C1 unsafe ptr::read of frame callback -> double-drop+aliasing UB; C2 padded_contains inverts padding (click region); C3 Box::leak font bytes on error/unbounded; C4 uv_bind_groups.len()-1 underflow; C5 public API panics on missing file/font; C6 [FONT DEBUG] println always on; C7 transform tests too weak; C8 Rectangle::pad asymmetric (unused); C9 replay drops keyboard input.
[PERF] P1 per-flush create_buffer_init+bind_group sprite batch; P2 same for atlas/glyph batch; P3 per-frame vertex buffer recreation of constants for every texture/atlas; P4 synchronous device.poll(Wait) stall per frame; P5 per-frame Vec<char> alloc in text layout; P6 String alloc per text draw; P7 O(atlas) pixel scan in debug print; P8 stable sort render queue every frame; P9 measure_text every frame for static text; P10 HashMap budget alloc per begin_frame; P11 rect identity bind group rebuilt each frame; P12 glow batch no pool; P13 svg raster load-time only (no-op).
